knocker
Homonym Number:
Word Class: noun
Sense Number:  1
Definition:a small leather pad on shearing blades [used to prevent clashing or overclosing.]


Origin: [none]
Register:
Register 2:
Flag: Farm Words
Domain: Rural
Region: [none]
See:
Pronunciation:
Notes:
Citations
Date:  4/11/1933
Source:  Press, The  (Acland Glossary)
Author:
Vol / Page:  15
Edition:
Quote:  knocker: a small leather pad fixed near the heel of shears to keep the blades from closing too far.
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1938
Source:  High Country: the evolution of a NZ Sheep Station
Author:  BURDON
Vol / Page:  84
Edition:
Quote:  A piece of rawhide known as a knocker is now used to prevent the shears clashing when closed.
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1951
Source:  NZ High Country
Author:  MCLEOD
Vol / Page:  26
Edition:
Quote:  The shearers buy their shears from the station and then proceed to cut them and bend them and embellish them with 'drivers', 'knockers', 'jockeys' and 'cockspurs' until their makers would hardly recognise them.
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1981
Source:  Loughnan Glossary
Author:  LOUGHNAN
Vol / Page:  47
Edition:
Quote:  knocker: piece of leather or cork placed near the heel of a blade shears to absorb the harsh click when the metal faces meet .. The knocker also prevents the blades from closing too far and thus gashing the ball of the thumb which lies in line with one blade.
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1974
Source:  Kingdom in the Hills
Author:  MCLEOD
Vol / Page:  91
Edition:
Quote:  He puts a 'driver' on it - a strap made of leather or lamp-wick which prevents his hand sliding forward on to the blades - and a 'knocker' which fits between the blades to stop the  jar and snap as he closes them.
Notes:
